      "text": "A middle-aged archeologist presents with a 5-day history of illness after returning from a 2-week trip to the Peruvian rainforest, where he unsuccessfully attempted to retrieve an ancient idol. Initially, he had sudden-onset fever to 40.8°C (105.4°F), severe headache, and vomiting. His fever broke 2 days ago but returned today, and he has developed severe abdominal pain, jaundice, and black vomit. He is confused, refusing to remove his hat, and muttering “It belongs in a museum.” Laboratory results show ALT 3150 U/L, AST 2893 U/L, platelets 45,000/μL, and PT 18 seconds. What is the most appropriate management approach?",
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 1,
          "text": "Yellow fever vaccination for immediate protection"
        },
        {
          "id": 2,
          "text": "Immediate liver biopsy for definitive diagnosis"
        },
        {
          "id": 3,
          "text": "Ibuoprofen for anti-inflammatory effects and pain management"
        },
        {
